<subSubSection id="9895F16059D581830D13D19796CAF7CF" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="BED2C6F615FB3834A63E0C66E2BE594C" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8AD46C416ACA0AE62010B3E168A4400D" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName id="6870A9BE0B7E4E59F9FA64D1DFDAA82E" class="Insecta" family="Platygastridae" genus="Pulchrisolia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pulchrisolia teras" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="teras">
<emphasis id="0F8FB1455D9CF3ECCE610476300EE58F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Pulchrisolia teras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is separated from all other species by the presence of deep notauli and well-defined preocellar depressions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A0A5B86712EED64911AE0156ADC9BD55" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="FFA308E23E9A6FD5EE5777E699225732" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="01CAC04175B14AE0FEAE9A08D90D39E4" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Taken from the Greek word for monster (tέρας), in reference to the size and appearance of this formidable creature. The epithet is treated as a noun in apposition.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
